      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "82f7a521-383b-4927-a0de-734149103d1d",
      "text": "Argument from ignorance ([[Richard Dawkins]] more poetically labelled this \"argument from lack of imagination\"), also known as appeal to ignorance, is a fallacy in informal logic. It asserts that a proposition is true because it has not yet been proven false or a proposition is false because it has not yet been proven true. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ce08dd399f5d0cec",
      "text": "This represents a type of false dichotomy in that it excludes a third option, which is that there may have been an insufficient investigation, and therefore there is insufficient information to prove the proposition be either true or false. Nor does it allow the admission that the choices may in fact not be two (true or false), but may be as many as four, - [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argument_from_ignorance wikipedia]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3ba552cae2e09667",
      "text": "- true\n- false\n- unknown between true or false\n- being unknowable (among the first three)."
    },
